1.HASONEVALUE()

Definition: Checks whether the column has been filtered down to exactly one distinct value.
Returns: TRUE/FALSE.

Syntax:
HASONEVALUE(<columnName>)

Example:

Say you have a slicer for Product[Category] with 3 categories: Electronics, Furniture, Clothing.

Slicer Selection	     HASONEVALUE(Product[Category])
--------------------------------------------------------
Nothing selected	           -    FALSE
Electronics	                 -    TRUE
Electronics + Furniture	     -    FALSE

üëâ Use Case: When you need to ensure only one distinct value is selected before calculating something.
-------------------------------------------------------------
Selected Category Sales = 
IF(
    HASONEVALUE(Product[Category]),
    SUM(Sales[Amount]),
    BLANK()
)
-------------------------------------------------------------

This will only show sales if exactly 1 category is selected.

2Ô∏è. HASONEFILTER()

Definition: Checks whether the column has a filter applied, regardless of whether it results in one or multiple values.
Returns: TRUE/FALSE.

Syntax:
HASONEFILTER(<columnName>)

Example:
Using the same slicer for Product[Category]:

Slicer Selection	          HASONEFILTER(Product[Category])
----------------------------------------------------------------
Nothing selected	                     FALSE
Electronics	                           TRUE
Electronics + Furniture              	 TRUE

üëâ Use Case: When you need to know if any filter at all is applied to the column, not just a single one.

Check Filter = 
IF(
    HASONEFILTER(Product[Category]),
    "Category is filtered",
    "No filter on Category"
)

‚úÖ Key Difference
Function	What It Checks	Example Scenario
HASONEVALUE()	Exactly one distinct value is left after filters	Validate slicer allows only 1 value (e.g., show customer details only if 1 customer is selected)
HASONEFILTER()	If any filter is applied (1 or many)	Adjust calculation if the column is filtered at all (e.g., show breakdown only when category filter is applied)
‚ö° Real-World Scenario

Imagine you‚Äôre building a Customer 360 dashboard:
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
You want to show customer profile details ‚Üí you must ensure exactly one customer is selected ‚Üí ‚úÖ HASONEVALUE(Customer[CustomerID]).

You want to show Sales by Category only if the user applied a filter on Category (doesn‚Äôt matter 1 or many) ‚Üí ‚úÖ HASONEFILTER(Product[Category]).

üëâ In short:
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
HASONEVALUE = strict ‚Üí exactly one
HASONEFILTER = loose ‚Üí at least one filter applied



HASONEFILTER = loose ‚Üí at least one filter applied
